The rest of this notebook works with one dynamic spectrum. Alias it here so it's easy to swap between spectra in the future. We'll use the zoomed spectrum, with 100 phases. Collect some info about the lines in this region.

dynspec = ca_spec

# Lines in this region of the spectrum:
# For info on air/vacuum conversino, see:
# Spectra - SDSS-III
# http://www.sdss3.org/dr8/spectro/spectra.php
# Atomic Data for Resonance Absorption Lines... - ADS
# https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1991ApJS...77..119M/abstract
# Ca II K line, air & vacuum:
CaK = [3933.663, 3934.777]
# Ca II H line, air & vacuum:
CaH = [3968.468, 3969.591]
lines = CaK + CaH
lines = (CaK[0], CaH[0])  # air only; appears to be what SOAP uses

# Compute average spectrum, and an "image" of the avg-subtracted 
# spectra (with time as the vertical dimension), rescaled.
avg = dynspec.active.sum(0) / dynspec.nphases
delta_image = dynspec.active - avg
l, u = delta_image.min(), delta_image.max()
ll, lu = dynspec.lambdas[0], dynspec.lambdas[-1]
delta_image = (delta_image - l)/(u - l)
In [9]:
# Compute and plot evolving spectral components via SVD.

if True:

    # Compute top 3 singular values and vectors; the largest singular value
    # has index 2 (i.e., they are increasing in s[:]).
    # U[phi,k] contains the phase basis function for singular value # k
    # Vt[k,lambda] contains the wavelength basis function for singular value # k
    U, s, Vt = linalg.svds(delta_image, k=3)

    outer = OuterProduct(dynspec.lambdas, Vt[-1,:], dynspec.phases, U[:,-1])
    f1 = outer.plot(lines)
    f1.axes[1].set_title('1st singular value')
    if save_figs:
        f1.savefig('Speclet+Modulator-1.png')

    outer = OuterProduct(dynspec.lambdas, Vt[-2,:], dynspec.phases, U[:,-2])
    # f2 = outer.plot(lines)
    f2 = outer.plot(lines, zoom=((3959.5, 3965.5), (-.24, .24)))
    f2.axes[1].set_title('2nd singular value')
    if save_figs:
        f2.savefig('Speclet+Modulator-2.png')

    outer = OuterProduct(dynspec.lambdas, Vt[-3,:], dynspec.phases, U[:,-3])
    # f3 = outer.plot(lines)
    f3 = outer.plot(lines, zoom=((3946.5, 3950.), (-.24, .24)))
    f3.axes[1].set_title('3rd singular value')
    if save_figs:
        f3.savefig('Speclet+Modulator-3.png')

    # *** DANGER: Changing xlim does not appear to affect the image as expected.
    # Just pass subsets of the data to zoom.
    if False:
        # Zoomed version of SVD3:
        outer = OuterProduct(dynspec.lambdas, Vt[-3,:], dynspec.phases, U[:,-3])
        f4 = outer.plot(lines)
        f4.axes[1].set_title('3rd singular value')
        xrng = (3946.5, 3950.)
        xrng = (3947.25, 3947.9)
        f4.axes[0].set_xlim(*xrng)
        f4.axes[1].set_xlim(*xrng)
        spec = dynspec.active[0,:]
        spec = spec/spec.max()
        l, u = Vt[-3,:].min(), Vt[-3,:].max()
        spec = spec*(u-l) + l
        f4.axes[1].plot(dynspec.lambdas, spec, 'g--', lw=1, alpha=.5)
        f4.axes[0].axvline(3948.05)
        f4.axes[1].axvline(3948.05)

    # Zoomed version of SVD3:
    i1, i2 = 7544, 7753  # very narrow region, for checking alignments
    i1, i2 = 7520, 7890
    lambdas = dynspec.lambdas[i1:i2]
    vvals = Vt[-3,i1:i2]
    outer = OuterProduct(lambdas, vvals, dynspec.phases, U[:,-3])
    f5 = outer.plot()
    spec = dynspec.active[0,:]
    spec = spec/spec.max()
    l, u = Vt[-3,:].min(), Vt[-3,:].max()
    # spec = spec*(u-l) + l  # v. center the spec curve
    spec = 1.2*u*spec  # keep spec curve > 0
    f5.axes[1].plot(dynspec.lambdas, spec, 'g--', lw=1, alpha=.5)
    f5.axes[1].axhline(0., ls='-', c='gray', lw=0.75)
    f5.axes[1].set_title('3rd singular value (zoomed)')
    if save_figs:
        f5.savefig('Speclet+Modulator-3-zoom.png')

#subset data to produce missing phases
#skip by 1,2,...,10 phases
#compute SVD with k=3 for each skip_value and return MSE of spectral basis, using the full data counterpart as ground truth

skip_max = 10
v1=np.zeros((skip_max,dynspec.lambdas.shape[0]))
v2=np.zeros((skip_max,dynspec.lambdas.shape[0]))
v3=np.zeros((skip_max,dynspec.lambdas.shape[0]))


for i in range(skip_max):
    spec_temp = dynspec.active[::(i+1),:]
    print(spec_temp.shape)
    avg = spec_temp.sum(0) / spec_temp.shape[0]
    delta_image2 = spec_temp - avg
    l, u = delta_image2.min(), delta_image2.max()
    delta_image2 = (delta_image2 - l)/(u - l)
    U, s, Vt2 = linalg.svds(delta_image2, k=3)
    v1[i,:]=Vt2[-1,:]
    v2[i,:]=Vt2[-2,:]
    v3[i,:]=Vt2[-3,:]

In [12]:
#MSE function for equal length vector, calculated as the average of term wise squared difference 
def vec_mse(x,y):
    a = ((x - y)**2).mean(axis=None)
    b = ((x + y)**2).mean(axis=None)
    return(min(a,b))

    m1[i] = vec_mse(v1[i,:],Vt[-1,:])
    m2[i] = vec_mse(v2[i,:],Vt[-2,:])
    m3[i] = vec_mse(v3[i,:],Vt[-3,:])

Randomly replicated subsampling in time¶

In [19]:
#100 time stamps total
tmin = 10
tmax = 90
tstep = 5
replica = 200

tsize = np.arange(tmin,tmax+1,tstep)
mse_matrix = np.zeros((tsize.size,replica,3))

for i in range(tsize.size):
    print(tsize[i])
    for j in range(replica):
        tchoose = random.choice(100,tsize[i],False) #random choose time stamps
        spec_temp = dynspec.active[tchoose,:]
        
        avg = spec_temp.sum(0) / spec_temp.shape[0] #de-mean data
        delta_image2 = spec_temp - avg
        l, u = delta_image2.min(), delta_image2.max()
        delta_image2 = (delta_image2 - l)/(u - l)
        
        U, s, Vt2 = linalg.svds(delta_image2, k=3) #do SVD
        
        mse_matrix[i,j,0] = vec_mse(Vt2[-1,:],Vt[-1,:])
        mse_matrix[i,j,1] = vec_mse(Vt2[-2,:],Vt[-2,:])
        mse_matrix[i,j,2] = vec_mse(Vt2[-3,:],Vt[-3,:])

print("table for number of time stamps used, mean_mse, se_mse, and se_%_mean")
tables = []
for i in range(3):   
    mse_mean = np.mean(mse_matrix[:,:,i],1)
    mse_se = np.std(mse_matrix[:,:,i],1)/np.sqrt(replica)
    mse_se_percent = mse_se/mse_mean*100
    out = np.stack((tsize,mse_mean, mse_se,mse_se_percent), axis=-1)
    tables.append(out)
    print()
    print(out)
    
tables = array(tables)
